{"action": "input", "code": "def get_translate_direction(input_grid: np.ndarray, relative_position: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid and the relative position of the red pixels and the teal pixels, this function determines the translate direction of the red pixels towards the teal pixels (only one direction, left or right or up or down).\n    \n    Parameters:\n    input_grid (np.ndarray): A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    relative_position (Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]): A tuple of two tuples representing the relative position of the red pixels and the teal pixels respectively.\n    \n    Returns:\n    Tuple[int, int]: A tuple representing the translate direction of the red pixels towards the teal pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    teal_row, teal_col = relative_position[0]\n    red_row, red_col = relative_position[1]\n    if teal_row == red_row:\n        if teal_col < red_col:\n            return (0, -1)\n        else:\n            return (0, 1)\n    elif teal_row < red_row:\n        return (-1, 0)\n    else:\n        return (1, 0)\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                                                 \n    In the input, you should see a shape of teal pixels and a shape of red pixels, you should get the relative position of the red pixels and the teal pixels.\n    then determine the translate direction of the red pixels towards the teal pixels (only one direction, left or right or up or down),          \n    and translate the red pixels towards the teal pixels until they touch each other (do not overlap).                                                                                              \n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    relative_position = get_relative_position(input_grid)\n    translate_direction = get_translate_direction(input_grid, relative_position)\n    output_grid = translate_red_pixels(input_grid, translate_direction)\n    return output_grid\ndef get_relative_position(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid, this function returns the relative position of the red pixels and the teal pixels.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    input_grid (np.ndarray): A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]: A tuple of two tuples representing the relative position of the red pixels and the teal pixels respectively.\n    \"\"\"\n    teal_pixels = np.where(input_grid == teal)\n    red_pixels = np.where(input_grid == red)\n    relative_position = ((teal_pixels[0][0], teal_pixels[1][0]), (red_pixels[0][0], red_pixels[1][0]))\n    return relative_position\ndef translate_red_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray, translate_direction: Tuple[int, int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid and the translate direction of the red pixels towards the teal pixels, this function translates the red pixels towards the teal pixels until they touch each other (do not overlap).\n    \n    Parameters:\n    input_grid (np.ndarray): A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    translate_direction (Tuple[int, int]): A tuple representing the translate direction of the red pixels towards the teal pixels.\n    \n    Returns:\n    np.ndarray: A 2D numpy array representing the output grid after translating the red pixels towards the teal pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    teal_row, teal_col = np.where(input_grid == teal)\n    red_row, red_col = np.where(input_grid == red)\n    while (red_row, red_col) != (teal_row, teal_col):\n        output_grid[red_row, red_col] = grey\n        red_row += translate_direction[0]\n        red_col += translate_direction[1]\n    output_grid[red_row, red_col] = green\n    return output_grid", "user_code": "def m