{"action": "edit", "code": "def get_relative_position(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid, returns the relative position of the teal and red pixels.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two tuples, where the first tuple represents the position of the teal pixels and the second tuple represents the position of the red pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    teal_pos = np.where(input_grid == teal)\n    red_pos = np.where(input_grid == red)\n    return ((teal_pos[0][0], teal_pos[1][0]), (red_pos[0][0], red_pos[1][0]))\ndef translate_red_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray, translate_direction: Tuple[int, int], translate_dist: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid, the translate direction, and the distance, translates the red pixels towards the teal pixels until they touch each other (do not overlap).\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    translate_direction: A tuple of two integers, where the first integer represents the row direction and the second integer represents the column direction in which the red pixels should be translated towards the teal pixels.\n    translate_dist: An integer representing the distance that the red pixels should be translated towards the teal pixels.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the output grid after translating the red pixels towards the teal pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    row_dir, col_dir = translate_direction\n    red_pos = np.where(input_grid == red)\n    teal_pos = np.where(input_grid == teal)\n    if row_dir != 0:\n        if row_dir > 0:\n            output_grid[red_pos[0][0]:red_pos[0][0] + translate_dist + 1, red_pos[1][0]] = 0\n            output_grid[teal_pos[0][0] - translate_dist:teal_pos[0][0] + 1, teal_pos[1][0]] = red\n        else:\n            output_grid[red_pos[0][0] - translate_dist:red_pos[0][0] + 1, red_pos[1][0]] = 0\n            output_grid[teal_pos[0][0]:teal_pos[0][0] + translate_dist + 1, teal_pos[1][0]] = red\n    elif col_dir > 0:\n        output_grid[red_pos[0][0], red_pos[1][0]:red_pos[1][0] + translate_dist + 1] = 0\n        output_grid[teal_pos[0][0], teal_pos[1][0] - translate_dist:teal_pos[1][0] + 1] = red\n    else:\n        output_grid[red_pos[0][0], red_pos[1][0] - translate_dist:red_pos[1][0] + 1] = 0\n        output_grid[teal_pos[0][0], teal_pos[1][0]:teal_pos[1][0] + translate_dist + 1] = red\n    return output_grid\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                                                 \n    In the input, you should see a shape of teal pixels and a shape of red pixels, you should get the relative position of the red pixels and the teal pixels.          \n    then determine the translate direction of the red pixels towards the teal pixels (only need one direction, left or right or up or down),                                 \n    and translate the red pixels towards the teal pixels until they touch each other (do not overlap).                                                                  \n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    relative_position = get_relative_position(input_grid)\n    translate_direction = get_translate_direction(input_grid, relative_position)\n    translate_dist = get_translate_distance(input_grid, translate_direction)\n    output_grid = translate_red_pixels(input_grid, translate_direction, translate_dist)\n    return output_grid\ndef get_translate_direction(input_grid: np.ndarray, relative_position: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid and the relative position of the teal and red pixels, returns the direction in which the red pixels should be translated towards the teal pixels.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    relative_position: A tuple of two tuples, where the first tuple represents the position of the teal pixels and the second tuple represents the position of the red pixels.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two integers, where the first integer represents the row direction and the second integer represents the column direction in which the red pixels should be translated towards the teal pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    teal_pos, red_pos = relative_position\n    row_dir = teal_pos[0] - red_pos[0]\n    col_dir = teal_pos[1] - red_pos[1]\n    if abs(row_dir) > abs(col_dir):\n        return (np.sign(row_dir), 0)\n    else:\n        return (0, np.sign(col_dir))\ndef get_translate_distance(input_grid: np.ndarray, translate_direction: Tuple[int, int]) -> int:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid and the translate direction, returns the distance that the red pixels should be translated towards the teal pixels.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    translate_direction: A tuple of two integers, where the first integer represents the row direction and the second integer represents the column direction in which the red pixels should be translated towards the teal pixels.\n    \n    Returns:\n    An integer representing the distance that the red pixels should be translated towards the teal pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    row_dir, col_dir = translate_direction\n    red_pos = np.where(input_grid == red)\n    teal_pos = np.where(input_grid == teal)\n    if row_dir != 0:\n        translate_dist = abs(red_pos[0][0] - teal_pos[0][0]) - 1\n    else:\n        translate_dist = abs(red_pos[1][0] - teal_pos[1][0]) - 1\n    return translate_dist", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:                                                                                                                         \n    \"\"\"                                            